[Knobbler](https://plugins.steinkamp.us/knobbler) turns a tablet into an auto-labeling, multitouch control surface for Ableton Live. It is an instrument, and instruments have a standard most apps don't have to meet: **latency you can feel.** A musician notices ~20ms. A page transition that takes a beat to appear isn't a loading state — it's a dropped cue.

I've written before about [trimming the OSC firehose](/posts/2026-05-26-knobbler-osc-diet) and [driving a fader from the UI thread](/posts/2026-05-26-sampling-a-spring). Those are about the _data_ moving between the Max for Live device and the app. This post is about the app's own _navigation_ — tapping between the knobbler, mixer, clips, and session pages — and why it used to sit on a stubborn floor of about three-quarters of a second per switch, identical on every page, no matter what I tried.

The punchline is that the floor was uniform _because_ it wasn't where I kept looking. Four lessons, each one a thing React Native already knew how to do that I'd hand-rolled around.

## Measure first

None of this is fixable by feel. I built a page-switch probe (`pageSwitchProbe.ts`, toggled in a debug panel) that timestamps each switch into its parts: `ui` (tap → the new page's React commit), `deviceWait` (request → the device's first reply chunk), and the stream/parse of whatever bulk payload follows. Everything below is that `ui` number — the part the app owns — on a production build, captured on two deliberately different devices: an iPad M1 (fast, 120Hz) and a Samsung Galaxy Tab A9+ (slow, 60Hz). The slow tablet is the one that tells the truth.

(`deviceWait` — the device's walk of Live's object model on a big set — is real, but it lives on the _other_ side of the wire, in the Max for Live device, so it's out of scope for an app-side post. I went after it separately, by [pooling the device's LiveAPI observers instead of churning them on every scroll](/posts/2026-06-03_knobblers-leaky-observers) — which also made the observer binding ~1.7x faster. Here it's enough to note that the data request fires synchronously _before_ the page mounts, so it overlaps the work below rather than stacking on it.)

## 1. Stop unmounting pages

The original design did the obvious thing: the active page was mounted, the others weren't. Switch pages, the old one unmounts, the new one mounts from scratch.

For most apps that's correct. For this one it's the whole problem, because mounting these pages is _expensive_: ~16 knobbler sliders cost about 300ms to mount, and the clip grid — every cell, every track header — runs about 1.5s on the Android tablet. You can't mount your way to instant. So the pages all have to stay alive and just hide when they're off-screen.

The naive way to keep a page mounted-but-hidden is `display: none`. That's the trap. On React Native's New Architecture (Fabric) with the gesture handler library, a `display: none` view **stays in the native view tree and its gesture handlers stay live in touch arbitration.** The hidden pages didn't stop existing — they kept competing for taps. A tap on a slider would change the track instead; the visible page's sliders went dead. Three resident pages, three sets of invisible gesture handlers all grabbing at the same touches.

The fix was to stop hand-rolling visibility and use the mechanism React Navigation itself uses: [`react-native-screens`](https://github.com/software-mansion/react-native-screens). Wrap the pages in a `<ScreenContainer hasTwoStates>` and give each a `<Screen activityState={isActive ? 2 : 0}>`. An inactive screen is **detached at the native level** — its views and handlers leave the hierarchy — while staying mounted in React. The page keeps its state and its expensive subtree; it just isn't in the touch-arbitration conversation when it's hidden.

It fixed the tap-stealing, and it was about 2x faster at switching than `display: none` besides. This became the spine of the whole effort, and it's the lesson I keep relearning on this app: **before you deepen a bespoke mechanism, check what the thousands of standard apps do.** This was my first native app, written solo before I had AI to argue with, so it's full of hand-rolled subsystems that the ecosystem already solved better.

## 2. The uniform floor was the context, not the pages

With every page now resident, I expected fast switches. Instead I got a flat ~700ms per switch — and suspiciously, _the same_ ~700ms on every page. Session, mixer, clips, knobbler: all within a few milliseconds of each other. When wildly different pages all cost exactly the same, the cost isn't in the pages.

It was in the React context. Knobbler keeps global state in one big `AppContext` whose value object is consumed by every strip, every slider, every clip cell. And the current page lived in that value. So `setCurrentPage` changed the context value, and **every consumer in every resident page re-rendered** — now that all five pages were mounted, a single page switch reconciled the entire app. The uniform floor was the context-value cascade; it had nothing to do with the destination page, which is exactly why every destination cost the same.

The fix is to get hot-path state _out_ of the broad value. The current page now lives in its own tiny context, read by the handful of components that actually care which page is showing. A switch re-renders those, not all 80 strips across five pages. I gave the same treatment to the other two fields that churn on interaction — the mixer's scroll window and the mapping/join mode — and left only stable handles (refs, setters, shared values that never trigger re-renders) in the big object.

This is the one with the headline number. iPad M1, large set, steady-state switch:

| page     | before (currentPage in broad context) | after (hot fields split out) |
| -------- | -------------------------------------- | ---------------------------- |
| session  | 710ms                                  | 100ms                        |
| mixer    | 718ms                                  | 82ms                         |
| clips    | 775ms                                  | 94ms                         |
| bluhand  | 732ms                                  | 54–67ms                      |
| knobbler | 723ms                                  | 69ms                         |

Roughly 7–11x per page, and — the tell that it was the right diagnosis — every page lifted at once, because there was only ever one cause.

## 3. Freeze the pages that aren't looking

A subtler version of the same disease survived the context split. Knobbler's OSC layer fires a global "tick" on every coalesced batch of incoming data — meter updates, clip state, name changes. Components subscribe to that tick to repaint. With every page resident, _every_ tick re-rendered every strip and cell on all five pages, even the four you couldn't see. The JS thread stayed saturated, and a saturated thread makes every switch feel slow regardless of how cheap the switch itself is.

Two cooperating fixes. Each page is memoized on its own visibility, so switching doesn't reconcile the _other_ resident pages. And each page subtree is wrapped so the tick subscription reads an "am I visible" context — when the page is hidden, it subscribes to a no-op, freezing the entire subtree without threading a prop through dozens of components. The always-visible chrome (toolbar, nav) has no such wrapper and ticks normally. Off-screen pages now cost nothing per tick; they sit detached and quiet until you bring them back.

## 4. Window the grid that can't be cheap

That left one genuinely heavy page: clips. The clip grid renders a cell per track per scene, and on a big set that's a lot of cells. Even with everything above, the first mount of clips was brutal on the slow tablet — and the unmount-era cost had been worse: a cold ClipsPage mount ran **3130–3159ms on Android**, making the whole switch to clips around six seconds.

The fix is virtualization — render only the visible window of columns, not all of them — but with a twist specific to this app. I'd reached for `FlatList` first, the standard answer, and it _broke_ here: inside a kept-mounted (hidden) page its scroll metrics go stale, and on re-show it prunes most of the strips until you manually scroll to wake it up. So this is the rare case where the hand-rolled path is correct — a plain `ScrollView` with JS-owned windowing math that derives the visible index range from the scroll position. It survives hide/show by construction because nothing about it depends on native layout metrics being fresh.

Windowing the track axis (the cells were already windowed) cut the cold mount hard:

| device        | clips mount, before | after       |
| ------------- | ------------------- | ----------- |
| iPad M1       | 1068–1200ms         | 307–316ms   |
| Galaxy Tab A9+ | 3130–3159ms        | 1436–1628ms |

And because the page now stays mounted, you only pay that once. A _re-show_ of clips on the Android tablet — repainting the windowed grid from cache instead of remounting every cell — is **144–182ms**, against the old ~3.1s mount. That's the ~18–22x win, and it's biggest on the device that suffered most.

## Where it landed

Put the four together — pages stay mounted and detach natively when hidden, hot state lives in narrow contexts, off-screen subtrees freeze, the heavy grid is windowed — and page switches across both devices and every set size now land in roughly **40–260ms**, down from the uniform ~700–775ms floor and the unmount-era multi-second mounts. On the iPad even a large set is ~40–100ms; on the slow tablet it's ~70ms on a small set, ~150–260ms on a large one, and clips specifically went from a three-second mount to a flat ~150ms re-show.

The first visit to each page still pays its mount once, and the device's object-model walk is its own story — I cut that down on the device side by [pooling its observers](/posts/2026-06-03_knobblers-leaky-observers) rather than from here. But the thing you _feel_, the second-and-later switch as you work a set, is now under the threshold where it reads as navigation instead of loading.

What ties the four lessons together is that three of them were me undoing something I'd hand-built — `display: none` instead of `react-native-screens`, one fat context instead of narrow ones, a global tick with no gate — and the fourth was knowing when _not_ to reach for the standard tool. The instinct that paid off every time was the same: when you hit a structural wall, the first question isn't "how do I patch this?" It's "how do the thousands of apps that already solved this solve it?" For an instrument, where the bar is a latency a musician can feel, that question is the difference between an app that loads and an app that's just _there_.
